Question 1:¶

Given some sample data, write a program to answer the following: click here to access the required data set

On Shopify, we have exactly 100 sneaker shops, and each of these shops sells only one model of shoe. We want to do some analysis of the average order value (AOV). When we look at orders data over a 30 day window, we naively calculate an AOV of $3145.13. Given that we know these shops are selling sneakers, a relatively affordable item, something seems wrong with our analysis.

Question 1a: Think about what could be going wrong with our calculation. Think about a better way to evaluate this data.¶

Initial Data Investigation¶

The first step I take when looking at a new dataset is to visualize the distribution of the data. This allows me to begin to identify any outliers and helps to inform later decisions. During this time I will also check for any null values, as those could be throwing off our observations.

Question 1a Conclusion:¶

Now that we have some information about our possible outlier shops, the next two questions I want to know in order to figure out what could be going wrong with our AOV calculation are as follows:

  • What percentage of the total revenue in this dataset is coming from bulk sneaker orders?
  • How many items is the average user of our platform purchasing?
In [ ]:
total_revenue_by_total_item = pd.DataFrame()
total_revenue_by_total_item["count_of_orders"] = data.total_items.value_counts()
total_revenue_by_total_item["total_order_amount"] = data.groupby("total_items")[
    "order_amount"
].sum()
total_revenue_by_total_item = total_revenue_by_total_item.rename_axis(
    "total_items"
).reset_index()
total_revenue_by_total_item["percent_total_order_amount"] = (
    total_revenue_by_total_item.total_order_amount
    / total_revenue_by_total_item["total_order_amount"].sum()
)
total_revenue_by_total_item["percent_count_of_orders"] = (
    total_revenue_by_total_item.count_of_orders
    / total_revenue_by_total_item["count_of_orders"].sum()
)
total_revenue_by_total_item.sort_values("total_items", ascending=True)

This pie chart tells us that the percentage of total Shopify sneaker buyers who are purchasing these bulk sneakers from Shop #42 is incredibly low. Only 0.34% of total Shopify sneaker buyers order these bulk orders of 2000 total items. The average user on Shopify who is buying sneakers is purchasing 1 or 2 pairs in each order.

The combination of these two data points reveals that the few records in the dataset from purchases from Store #42 do in fact tremendously skew the distribution of the order_amount variable to the right (or a positive skew). This then effects the AOV and skews that in the same direction.

Question 1b:¶

What metric would you report for this dataset?¶

For this dataset I would want to report a metric that accomplishes the same goals as AOV, so it is first important to recognize what those are. We are trying to use AOV to gauge how much money per order the average Shopify shop selling sneakers is making. In order to get this average, AOV looks at the overall average & central tendency of our dataset, however we now know that this is skewed because of the bulk orders from Shop #42. This means AOV is in fact capturing a higher area of our domain.

  • We know that total_items varies dramatically between orders, which directly effects the AOV calculation for those orders. A sneaker buying customer may buy anywhere from 1 to 2000 pairs in a single order.
  • We also know that some stores (Shop #42 specifically) will sell bulk orders of 2,000 shoes per order priced at \$352 a pair. This is a very different selling practice than luxury stores like Shop #78 which will sell a pair of sneakers for no less than \$25,725 and has never sold more than 6 pairs in a single order. By including these shops in the same AOV calculation, we are including outliers and distorting the story of the average shop in our dataset.

A luxury Sneaker shop such as Shop #78 will end up having a much higher AOV than a shop that sells their sneakers at a lower price point.

A potential solution to the first problem is to continue classifying orders into bins depending on the total amount of items in each order. By doing this we separate out the bulk customers from other shoppers in order to get a more complete view of our customer base.

In [ ]:
aov_by_total_item = pd.DataFrame()
aov_by_total_item["count_of_orders"] = data.total_items.value_counts()
aov_by_total_item["total_order_amount"] = data.groupby("total_items")[
    "order_amount"
].sum()
aov_by_total_item = aov_by_total_item.rename_axis("total_items").reset_index()

aov_by_total_item["Average Order Value"] = np.round(
    aov_by_total_item.total_order_amount / aov_by_total_item.count_of_orders, 2
)
aov_by_total_item = aov_by_total_item.sort_values("total_items")
aov_by_total_item = aov_by_total_item.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=False)
aov_by_total_item

Looking at this chart we can see that AOV varies significantly depending on the total_items ordered. The vast majority of our sneaker buying customers are purchasing 1, 2, or sometimes 3 total items. The AOV for these orders is significantly smaller than our previously calculated AOV of \$3,145.13. This, again, points to outliers skewing our dataset.

An initial idea I had to address this problem was to weight the AOV by a measure like standard deviation. This would measure how far away from the mean order amount our values are, which we could use to lessen the impact of outliers.

Question 1c:¶

What is its value?¶

Instead of using standard deviation I have desired to instead calculate a different metric. By modifying our calculation for AOV to instead look at the median order_amount in each of our bins instead of the average we can calculate a metric that accomplishes the same goals as AOV while better representing the tendencies of our sales dataset. This is because the median tends to be less impacted by outliers than the mean/average value. We know this dataset is skewed to the right so the average will be higher then the median.

This new metric is the Median Order Value, or MOV, which informs us about the dollar value in our sales data is that lies between the second and third quartile. This metric gives us another method of understanding our sales distribution but it is important to note that a change in MOV does not necessarily mean a change in how sales are going overall.

It changes as shops sell sneakers below/above the median. It is therefor best to include this metric alongside AOV as well as the standard deviation of each total_items group. This allows us to gather a more complete understanding of our sneaker sales dataset.

The difference between MOV and AOV provides Shopify researchers with an estimate of how much & in which direction the data is skewed. Including standard deviation lets researchers get an idea of the variance within each group.

In [ ]:
MOV_calc = data.groupby("total_items")["order_amount"].median()
MOV_calc = MOV_calc.reset_index(name="MOV")
aov_by_total_item["Median Order Value"] = MOV_calc["MOV"]
aov_by_total_item

The Median Order Value for the entire dataset (without grouping by total_items) is $284.00. This is $2,861.13 less than the Average Order Value of the dataset which is $3,145.13

This tells us that there is a significant amount of Shopify users purchasing cheaper sneakers and that the outliers of Shop #42 (selling bulk) and Shop #78 (selling luxury sneakers) significantly impact our previously calculated AOV.

Question 2:¶

Question 2a:¶

SELECT ShipperName, COUNT(Orders.ShipperID)
FROM Orders
INNER JOIN Shippers ON Orders.ShipperID = Shippers.ShipperID
GROUP BY Orders.ShipperID;

How many orders were shipped by Speedy Express in total?
In total there were 54 orders shipped by Speedy Express.

Question 2b:¶

SELECT LastName, COUNT(Orders.EmployeeID)
FROM Orders
INNER JOIN Employees ON Orders.EmployeeID = Employees.EmployeeID
GROUP BY Orders.EmployeeID
Order by COUNT(Orders.EmployeeID) Desc;

What is the last name of the employee with the most orders?
"Peacock" is the last name of the employee with the most orders.

Question 2c:¶

SELECT ProductName, Quantity
FROM(
    SELECT Products.ProductName as ProductName, OrderDetails.Quantity
    FROM Orders
    INNER JOIN Customers ON Orders.CustomerID=Customers.CustomerID
    INNER JOIN OrderDetails ON Orders.OrderID=OrderDetails.OrderID
    INNER JOIN Products ON Products.ProductID=OrderDetails.ProductID
    WHERE Country = 'Germany'
    Group By Products.ProductID
    Order by  OrderDetails.Quantity Desc);

What product was ordered the most by customers in Germany?
"Steeleye Stout" was ordered 100 times, which is the most by customers in Germany. This had more german buyers than any other product.
